‚Äú1. The polio story as you learned it is wrong. It‚Äôs one of the most often misunderstood sequence of events in the last two hundred years. I wanted to explain a few things about the disease to help people understand what actually happened.
2. The first modern account of something resembling polio was in 1789. A physician named Michael Underwood described an illness in children he called ‚ÄúDebility of the Lower Extremities.‚Äù He attributed it to teething and foul bowels.
3. One of the next mentions was from Louisiana in 1841. A few children came down with paralysis. The supposed cause: teething. Why would teething be associated with paralysis?
4. Various stories appeared throughout the 1800s of children coming down with paralysis, almost always in their legs. Many people called it ‚Äúteething paralysis,‚Äù but others settled on ‚Äúinfantile paralysis.‚Äù
5. This was a new phenomenon: Doctors had never seen it before and didn‚Äôt know why it was happening. Research began to reveal that the cause of paralysis were lesions on the grey part of the spinal cord.
6. If you developed a lesion on your spinal cord, they called this a ‚Äúpoliomyelitis.‚Äù Polio = grey. Myelitis = inflammation of the spinal cord.
7. A poliomyelitis was a lesion on your spinal cord. You could have more than one of them. But they didn‚Äôt know why children had begun developing them, seemingly out of nowhere
8. Scientists conducted research on animals by purposefully poisoning them with arsenic, an ingredient of popular medical remedies of the time. The result? Paralysis in their hind legs.

Have you seen these little critters in your soil? üëÄ

‚Ä¢Soil Mites üêú
Hard to see by the naked eye and fast moving. You may see them in your new bag of soil. They prefer wet and damp soil environments but can survive in dry soil for some time. They improve soil structure, soil nutrients and encourage plant growth by releasing spores of mycorrhizael fungi. Do not panic/mistake them for spider mites, whereas soil mites are only found on/in the soil and maybe on your planter. 

I truly forgot soil mites even existed until I saw them swarming all over the soil of my Dieffenbachia Amy. 
#planttips #beneficialinsects #planttok #plantcare #CapCut
